<DOC><DOCNO> AP880622-0100 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 1020EST</FILEID><FIRST>r p PM-NewJersey-Jackson     06-22 0245</FIRST><SECOND>PM-New Jersey-Jackson,290</SECOND><HEAD>Jackson Gets Eight More New Jersey Delegates in Deal</HEAD><BYLINE>By JO ASTRID GLADING</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>HAMILTON TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   New Jersey Democrats defused agrowing party dispute by increasing Jesse Jackson's delegation atthe Democratic National Convention next month in Atlanta.   The compromise reached Tuesday night between supporters ofJackson and Michael Dukakis gives Jackson eight more delegates, inaddition to the nine delegates he won in the June 7 primary.   Jackson's supporters felt he deserved more than nine delegatesbecause he won 33 percent of the popular vote.   Newark Mayor Sharpe James, who was elected as one of the Jacksondelegates, said he was confident his candidate's voice will beheard at the convention.   ``Those of us who support and worked hard for Jesse Jackson goto the Democratic Convention in Atlanta next month are optimisticthat many of the goals and principles of the Jackson campaign willbe embodied within the Democratic party platform,'' James said.   He said state Democrats must work after the convention to changeNew Jersey's winner-take-all delegate system that left Jackson with33 percent of the popular vote but only 12 percent of the delegates.   ``We need to restructure our delegate districts more fairly sothat the strength of urban voters is not diluted,'' James said.   State Democratic leaders also voted to send AcadamyAward-winning actress Olympia Dukakis to the convention next monthin Atlanta as an at-large delegate for Dukakis, her cousin.</TEXT></DOC>